What is a Consecutive Sequence?
A consecutive sequence is a set of numbers that come one after another, without skipping any number, and in order.

ğŸ§  In simpler terms:
The numbers increase (or decrease) by exactly 1.

No gaps allowed.

âœ… Examples of Consecutive Sequences:
ğŸ“ˆ Increasing:
[1, 2, 3, 4, 5] âœ…

[7, 8, 9] âœ…

[10, 11, 12, 13, 14] âœ…

ğŸ“‰ Decreasing (also considered consecutive in some cases):
[5, 4, 3, 2, 1] âœ… (if order doesn't matter)

[3, 2, 1] âœ…

âŒ Not Consecutive:
[1, 3, 4] âŒ (because 2 is missing)

[10, 12, 13] âŒ (because 11 is missing)

[1, 2, 2, 3] âŒ (duplicate breaks the sequence)

"Find the longest consecutive sequence in an array."

Input: [100, 4, 200, 1, 3, 2]

Output: 4 (because 1, 2, 3, 4 is the longest sequence)

